No one can reliably answer this. In 2014, few predicted transformers; in 2019, few predicted GPT-3's scale; in 2022, few predicted ChatGPT's societal impact. Extrapolating 10 years in AI is speculative fiction, not forecasting.

Current leading contenders (Gemini, GPT, Claude, Grok) will likely be unrecognizable architectures by then. Scaling laws may hit physical or economic limits, forcing architectural shifts. Neuromorphic, optical, or quantum substrates could displace current GPU-based training. Mixture-of-experts and test-time compute are already changing what "leading" means.

The org that wins may not exist yet, or may be a national project from China, the EU, or India. Regulatory fragmentation could mean no single "leading" model globally. "Leading" itself may splinter: best reasoning, best multimodal, best on-device, best agentic.

Honest answer: unknown.
